<subSubSection id="C34665385B5CA9073BD8306DFCD5FF5F" lastPageId="58" lastPageNumber="59" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BE336B35B5CA9073BD8306DFCD5FF5F" blockId="57.[151,1438,1716,1955]" lastBlockId="58.[151,1435,151,213]" lastPageId="58" lastPageNumber="59" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis id="B928EAA15B5CA9043BD8306DFEBFF8D1" bold="true" box="[199,315,1860,1885]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is unique and could be easily distinguished from its congeners by: 1) body large size (
<quantity id="4CA49B565B5CA9043B80304EFE8EF80C" box="[159,266,1895,1920]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0699999999999998" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" unit="mm" value="10.7">10.7 mm</quantity>
); 2) temple quite dilated; 3) punctures on dorsal side of head deep and densely distributed, interspaces shorter than half of a puncture’s diameter; 4) punctures on dorsal surface of pronotum arranged in 7–8 paired rows; 5) mesoscutellum bearing polygonal reticulum; 6) punctures on dorsal surface of elytra bearing more than ten rows on each side; 7) dorsal surface of abdomen bearing transverse microstriae and densely distributed, rounded punctures, interspaces ca. a punctures’ diameter; 8) arcuate posterior margin of male abdominal tergite VIII, attached a small, median triangular notch; 9) unique inner sac.
</paragraph>
